<br>
Ozone<br>
Null-gravity field<br>
Polutionless (noise and emmissions) exhaust<br>
<br>
All three of these have been created.  Null-gravity by a team of swedish / german scientists.  The polutionless exhaust system was made in North Carolina.  What do all three have in common?  <br>
<br>
We don't have them EVERYWHERE in the world because it would hurt the pocket book of too many people who have lots of money and don't want to loose it.  They're too expensive to impliment or would take away too much profit.  Greed again.<br>
<br>
As for water itself.  Yes, this ecosystem acts a lot like energy.  We cannot just arbitrarily destroy the total amount of water any more than we can destroy the energy of a volcano.  The water is not going out into space.  Two places the water is going are the oceans and the polar ice caps.  <br>
<br>
In the first place, more than 70% of the fresh water in the world is held in the polar ice caps.  If we want water, all we have to do is transport and melt that ice.  But that takes money.  Secondly, man-made global meteorlogical effects (Greenhouse, South-Asian black cloud) are causing a rise in global tempatures which is throwing the normal rain-evaporation patterns askew.<br>
<br>
Mankind does need to act soon to correct these issues.  But, in my cynical opinion, he will look for cheaper ways to stem the problem without ever fixing it.  Either mankind will suffer a massive, global loss of life; or a global change of social/economic/political thought will solve this and several other problems.<br>
<br>
But to that end, Im hoping for a near-utopian global society.  Fat chance huh? <p>Iovox, Cleric of Rodect Nife
